  "text": "Six criteria for IS project selection are considered, including outside environment conditions ( 1 ), expected returns ( 2 ), development costs ( 3 ), project risks ( 4 ), degree of ease to operate ( 5 ), and management ability of the organization ( 6 ). Criteria on development costs ( 3 ) and project risks ( 4 ) are cost criteria, and the others are benefit ones. The three decision makers ( = 1, 2, 3) use the linguistic variables shown in Table 2 to evaluate the ratings of the alternatives ( = 1, 2, 3, 4) with respect to the criteria ( = 1, 2, 3 , . . . , 6) and construct, respectively, the decision matrix ( ) ( = 1, 2, 3) as listed in Tables 3, 4 , and 5. This is a hybrid MCGDM problem involving four different data types: exact values, intervals, linguistic terms, and IFNs. To solve this issue, we apply the developed method to the ranking and selection of the alternative IS project below. Three criteria including outside environment conditions ( 1 ), project risks ( 4 ) and management ability of the organization ( 6 ) are expressed in the types of linguistic terms, criterion on expected returns ( 2 ) is expressed in the interval forms, criterion on development costs ( 3 ) is exact values and criterion on degree of ease to operate ( 5 ) is expressed in the form of intuitionistic fuzzy numbers. In selection process, each decision maker expresses his/her preferences depending on the nature of the alternatives and on his/her own knowledge over them. The hybrid decision matries [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] , and [CITATION_3] are given by the decision maker 1 , 2 , and 3 , are shown as follows.",
